Tw: lots of details about mental illness 

It took me forever to post this. This routine is very emotional for me to share, especially now weeks later, as I go through a traumatic and tragic time. 

This piece is an ode to my mental illness. The past 12 months have been the toughest and most unstable of my life. I've suffered from often debilitating flashbacks due to PTSD, I endured intense EMDR therapy that reopened old wounds that ran deep, I suffered a relapse of an old eating disorder that wrecked my body and mind for months, I felt heavy with crippling depression, I fought intrusive thoughts so loud that on a few occasions I didn't know how I'd survive. It's been a journey to go through diagnosing what's going on and finding med management that keeps me afloat. And in the midst of all this, I did the worst thing possible - I isolated. I ate my suffering in silence and rarely let loved ones outside my household know the extent of what was wrong. I pushed everyone away and dug a comfortable pit for myself. 

This piece is dedicated to an important lesson I've learned - let yourself be embraced. Allow people who love you to show up for you. I had to claw myself out of that pit I dug and open myself up to support and care. I always get so frustrated hearing, "Check on your strong friends," Meanwhile, I wouldn't let myself be checked on. 

I wanted to create a routine that captured it all - isolation, dissociation, depression, desperation,mania, and eventually surrendering to support. For months, this routine became like therapy (in addition to regular therapy, of course). It was created the way it was born - in total isolation until I was ready to share.  So here I am, opened all the way up for what ended up being my most important routine to date. Special thanks to those close to me who held my hand along the way and continue to hold me, especially the one person who intimately knows my struggle, @shirorx . Thank you, @yulikapoleposition, for being a part of something truly special to me. You are the best human prop 🥹.

If you ever feel lost in your pit, let yourself reach up and hold the hand of the one who grabs for you to pull you out. 💕

So excited to get my official video back from @intlpoleconvention ! After a very emotional and heavy piece competing at APC, I was thrilled to just do something fun and sassy for Polecon. This year, my goal was to get more comfortable in heels and strengthen my ankles (ask literally anyone who danced with me in DC - my heel game was non-existant). Delivering this routine was a result of working on that goal. 

Thank you to my @verticaladdicts_ family for all the support in creating this routine and for cheering me on at Polecon! Thanks @jenijanoisliquid for letting me open the showcase :) Special thanks to all my DC area friends who came out to cheer, too! It's so special that I've gotten to go back to my old home twice in a few months, both times for pole. I'm glad I could leave you this time with a little bit of cheeks and clacks 😜

TW: Pregnancy loss

A few weeks before Polecon, I experienced a devastating pregnancy loss (which is redundant because when is it not devestating?). I had won this photoshoot at Polecon and had secretly gotten excited for it to be a fun capture of early pregnancy. I had a few weeks of thinking of how my life was going to change, what the future would look like, and even started to rethink choreography for my performance to be more pregnant friendly. 

And then suddenly that future disappeared. It was gone before I could even start it. We were devastated and heartbroken. It changed my life. I've been solemn these past few weeks, thinking about how I would have been sharing a pregnancy announcement, but now I'm not. Just these nice pictures of me, myself, and I. I share this now because hearing the stories from other women helped me. This absolutely crushing circumstance is far more common than you know, and I felt less lonely in my grief because others embraced me and shared their experiences. For that, I will be forever grateful.

While this photoshoot did not end up being the first trimester shoot I thought it would be, I was still happy to give myself a chance to embrace my body, which I felt so disconnected from after what happened. Polecon turned out to be so healing and reviving after spending weeks withdrawing. 

I see these smiles and these beautiful photos, and remember how I tried to find something nice amidst tragedy. I'm reminded that you never know what lies behind a smile for someone. I'm still on a journey of grief. And perhaps it'll always be there. Thank you to those who have held my hand in this journey. Your compassion has meant the world.

Sometimes people ask me how/why I perform so often. The truth is, I feel myself slow down and regress when I don't. It's only been since June since my last performance, but when I went to practice yesterday for an upcoming competition, I really felt it. My skin is sensitive, my climbs feel heavy, my handstands are weaker, etc. Why do I perform? To keep my body moving so I don't lose it. That and I love me any excuse to get creative and bring new ideas to life, and I'm all about the rush you get performing for a crowd :) The physical benefit is just a nice bonus.

I returned to teaching this week, and it feels so good to be back! I've taught this choreo in Intro to Pole at @verticaladdicts_ the last couple days, and I was so stoked that my class today did 2.5 minutes of choreo in one hour today! @mariahcarey would be so proud of our holiday spirit 👏🏼
